# Linux Platform Services: File Pickers, Notifications, and Native Integration

*Master the 20+ platform services that bridge your MAUI app with Linux desktop environments, from xdg-desktop-portal to D-Bus notifications and encrypted secure storage.*

## Introduction to Platform Services

When building .NET MAUI applications for Linux, one of the most critical challenges is integrating with the diverse ecosystem of desktop environments. Unlike Windows or macOS, where platform APIs are standardized and consistent, Linux presents a fragmented landscape: GNOME users expect different behaviors than KDE users, Wayland sessions require different approaches than X11, and minimal window managers may lack services entirely.

**OpenMaui.Controls.Linux** tackles this complexity head-on with a comprehensive suite of 20+ platform services that provide native integration while maintaining 100% MAUI API compatibility. These services handle everything from file dialogs and notifications to secure credential storage and system clipboard access.

The architecture follows a three-tier strategy:

1. **Primary integration**: Use freedesktop.org standards (xdg-desktop-portal, D-Bus specifications, Secret Service API)
2. **Desktop-specific fallbacks**: Leverage environment-specific tools (zenity for GNOME, kdialog for KDE)
3. **Command-line alternatives**: Provide basic functionality through universal CLI tools when GUI services are unavailable

This approach ensures your application works seamlessly across Ubuntu, Fedora, Arch Linux, and even minimal distributions, while respecting user preferences and desktop environment conventions.

```csharp
// Platform services are automatically registered during MAUI initialization
var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
builder.UseMauiApp<App>();

// All standard MAUI platform services are available:
// - IFilePicker
// - INotificationManager  
// - ISecureStorage
// - IClipboard
// - ILauncher
// - IShare
// - IBrowser
```

The beauty of this implementation is that as a MAUI developer, you use the exact same APIs you'd use on Windows or Android—the platform abstraction handles all the Linux-specific complexity behind the scenes.

## File System Access: xdg-desktop-portal and Fallbacks

File pickers are one of the most visible platform integrations in any desktop application. Users expect native file dialogs that match their desktop environment's look and feel. OpenMaui achieves this through a sophisticated fallback chain that prioritizes modern standards while ensuring compatibility.

## The xdg-desktop-portal Standard

**xdg-desktop-portal** is the modern freedesktop.org standard for sandboxed applications to access system resources. It provides a D-Bus API that desktop environments implement, ensuring consistent behavior whether you're running GNOME, KDE Plasma, or elementary OS.

OpenMaui's `FilePicker` service first attempts to use xdg-desktop-portal by invoking the `org.freedesktop.portal.FileChooser` D-Bus interface:

```csharp
public class LinuxFilePicker : IFilePicker
{
    public async Task<FileResult> PickAsync(PickOptions options = null)
    {
        // Attempt 1: xdg-desktop-portal (modern standard)
        if (IsXdgPortalAvailable())
        {
            return await PickViaXdgPortalAsync(options);
        }

        // Attempt 2: Desktop-specific tools
        if (IsZenityAvailable()) // GNOME/GTK environments
        {
            return await PickViaZenityAsync(options);
        }

        if (IsKDialogAvailable()) // KDE Plasma
        {
            return await PickViaKDialogAsync(options);
        }

        // Attempt 3: Graceful degradation
        throw new PlatformNotSupportedException(
            "No file picker available. Install xdg-desktop-portal, zenity, or kdialog."
        );
    }
}
```

## Desktop Environment Fallbacks

When xdg-desktop-portal isn't available (common on older distributions or minimal installations), OpenMaui falls back to environment-specific tools:

**Zenity** (GNOME/GTK environments):
```bash
zenity --file-selection --title="Select a file" --file-filter="Images | *.png *.jpg *.jpeg"
```

**KDialog** (KDE Plasma):
```bash
kdialog --getopenfilename ~ "Images (*.png *.jpg *.jpeg)"
```

These tools are invoked via `Process.Start()` with output captured from stdout, providing a native experience that matches the user's desktop theme.

## Practical Usage

From your MAUI application, file picking is straightforward:

```csharp
public partial class MainPage : ContentPage
{
    public async Task SelectImageAsync()
    {
        var customFileType = new FilePickerFileType(
            new Dictionary<DevicePlatform, IEnumerable<string>>
            {
                { DevicePlatform.Linux, new[] { "image/png", "image/jpeg" } },
                { DevicePlatform.WinUI, new[] { ".png", ".jpg" } },
            });

        var result = await FilePicker.PickAsync(new PickOptions
        {
            PickerTitle = "Select an image",
            FileTypes = customFileType
        });

        if (result != null)
        {
            var stream = await result.OpenReadAsync();
            MyImage.Source = ImageSource.FromStream(() => stream);
        }
    }
}
```

## Multiple File Selection and Folders

The implementation supports both single and multiple file selection, as well as folder picking:

```csharp
// Pick multiple files
var results = await FilePicker.PickMultipleAsync(new PickOptions
{
    FileTypes = FilePickerFileType.Images
});

foreach (var file in results)
{
    Console.WriteLine($"Selected: {file.FileName}");
}

// Pick a folder (uses xdg-desktop-portal SelectFolder method)
var folder = await FolderPicker.PickAsync();
if (folder != null)
{
    Console.WriteLine($"Folder: {folder.Path}");
}
```

The three-tier fallback strategy ensures that whether your users are running the latest Ubuntu with full portal support or a minimal Arch Linux installation with just kdialog, they'll get a functional, native-looking file picker.

## Notifications with libnotify and D-Bus

Desktop notifications are essential for keeping users informed without disrupting their workflow. Linux notifications follow the freedesktop.org Desktop Notifications Specification, implemented via D-Bus by all major desktop environments.

## D-Bus Notification Architecture

OpenMaui's notification system communicates directly with the `org.freedesktop.Notifications` D-Bus service, which is implemented by notification daemons in GNOME (gnome-shell), KDE (plasma-workspace), XFCE (xfce4-notifyd), and others.

```csharp
public class LinuxNotificationManager : INotificationManager
{
    private const string DbusService = "org.freedesktop.Notifications";
    private const string DbusPath = "/org/freedesktop/Notifications";
    private const string DbusInterface = "org.freedesktop.Notifications";

    public async Task ShowAsync(NotificationRequest request)
    {
        // Invoke D-Bus Notify method
        var notificationId = await InvokeDbusNotifyAsync(
            appName: "MyMauiApp",
            replacesId: 0,
            appIcon: request.Image ?? "dialog-information",
            summary: request.Title,
            body: request.Description,
            actions: new string[] { },
            hints: new Dictionary<string, object>(),
            expireTimeout: -1 // Use server default
        );

        // Store ID for potential cancellation
        _activeNotifications[request.NotificationId] = notificationId;
    }
}
```

## Notification Features

The D-Bus specification supports rich notification features:

**Basic Notifications:**
```csharp
await NotificationManager.ShowAsync(new NotificationRequest
{
    Title = "Build Complete",
    Description = "Your application compiled successfully.",
    NotificationId = 1001
});
```

**Notifications with Icons:**
```csharp
await NotificationManager.ShowAsync(new NotificationRequest
{
    Title = "New Message",
    Description = "You have 3 unread messages.",
    Image = "/usr/share/icons/hicolor/48x48/apps/mail.png",
    NotificationId = 1002
});
```

**Action Buttons:**
While MAUI's `NotificationRequest` doesn't directly support actions, you can extend the implementation to use D-Bus action capabilities:

```csharp
// Extended implementation with action support
var hints = new Dictionary<string, object>
{
    { "urgency", 2 }, // Critical urgency (0=low, 1=normal, 2=critical)
    { "category", "im.received" } // Notification category
};

var actions = new[] 
{ 
    "reply", "Reply",
    "mark-read", "Mark as Read" 
};

var id = await InvokeDbusNotifyAsync(
    "ChatApp",
    0,
    "dialog-information",
    "New Message from Alice",
    "Hey, are you free for lunch?",
    actions,
    hints,
    5000 // 5 second timeout
);
```

## libnotify Fallback

For systems where D-Bus isn't accessible programmatically, OpenMaui can fall back to the `notify-send` command-line tool (part of libnotify):

```bash
notify-send "Build Complete" "Your application compiled successfully." --icon=dialog-information
```

This is invoked via:

```csharp
private async Task ShowViaNotifySendAsync(NotificationRequest request)
{
    var process = new Process
    {
        StartInfo = new ProcessStartInfo
        {
            FileName = "notify-send",
            Arguments = $"\"{request.Title}\" \"{request.Description}\" --icon=dialog-information",
            UseShellExecute = false,
            CreateNoWindow = true
        }
    };

    process.Start();
    await process.WaitForExitAsync();
}
```

## Notification Persistence and Cancellation

The implementation tracks active notifications and supports cancellation:

```csharp
public async Task CancelAsync(int notificationId)
{
    if (_activeNotifications.TryGetValue(notificationId, out var dbusId))
    {
        // Call CloseNotification D-Bus method
        await InvokeDbusMethodAsync(
            DbusService,
            DbusPath,
            DbusInterface,
            "CloseNotification",
            new object[] { dbusId }
        );

        _activeNotifications.Remove(notificationId);
    }
}
```

This D-Bus-first approach ensures notifications appear with the correct desktop theme, support the user's notification preferences (Do Not Disturb mode, notification positioning), and integrate seamlessly with notification history features in GNOME and KDE.

## Secure Storage: libsecret and Encrypted Alternatives

Storing sensitive data like API tokens, passwords, and encryption keys requires platform-specific secure storage mechanisms. On Linux, the standard solution is the **Secret Service API**, implemented by GNOME Keyring (libsecret) and KDE Wallet.

## The Secret Service API

The Secret Service is a D-Bus API defined by freedesktop.org that provides encrypted storage with automatic unlocking when users log in. OpenMaui's `SecureStorage` implementation uses this as the primary storage mechanism:

```csharp
public class LinuxSecureStorage : ISecureStorage
{
    private const string DbusService = "org.freedesktop.secrets";
    private const string CollectionPath = "/org/freedesktop/secrets/aliases/default";

    public async Task SetAsync(string key, string value)
    {
        if (IsSecretServiceAvailable())
        {
            await StoreViaSecretServiceAsync(key, value);
        }
        else
        {
            await StoreViaEncryptedFileAsync(key, value);
        }
    }

    private async Task StoreViaSecretServiceAsync(string key, string value)
    {
        // Create a secret item with attributes for searching
        var attributes = new Dictionary<string, string>
        {
            { "application", "MyMauiApp" },
            { "key", key }
        };

        var properties = new Dictionary<string, object>
        {
            { "org.freedesktop.Secret.Item.Label", $"MyMauiApp: {key}" },
            { "org.freedesktop.Secret.Item.Attributes", attributes }
        };

        // Store encrypted value
        await InvokeSecretServiceCreateItemAsync(
            CollectionPath,
            properties,
            value,
            replace: true
        );
    }
}
```

## Using Secure Storage in Your App

From your MAUI application, secure storage uses the familiar cross-platform API:

```csharp
public class AuthService
{
    public async Task SaveTokenAsync(string token)
    {
        await SecureStorage.SetAsync("auth_token", token);
    }

    public async Task<string> GetTokenAsync()
    {
        try
        {
            return await SecureStorage.GetAsync("auth_token");
        }
        catch (Exception ex)
        {
            // Handle cases where keyring is locked or unavailable
            Console.WriteLine($"Failed to retrieve token: {ex.Message}");
            return null;
        }
    }

    public async Task ClearTokenAsync()
    {
        SecureStorage.Remove("auth_token");
    }
}
```

## Encrypted File Fallback

When the Secret Service is unavailable (headless systems, minimal installations, or locked keyrings), OpenMaui falls back to an encrypted file-based storage mechanism:

```csharp
private async Task StoreViaEncryptedFileAsync(string key, string value)
{
    var storagePath = Path.Combine(
        Environment.GetFolderPath(Environment.SpecialFolder.LocalApplicationData),
        "secure_storage"
    );

    Directory.CreateDirectory(storagePath);

    // Derive encryption key from machine-specific data
    var machineKey = GetMachineSpecificKey();

    // Encrypt using AES-256
    var encryptedValue = EncryptAes256(value, machineKey);

    // Store with restricted permissions (0600)
    var filePath = Path.Combine(storagePath, $"{key}.enc");
    await File.WriteAllBytesAsync(filePath, encryptedValue);

    // Set file permissions to owner-only read/write
    SetFilePermissions(filePath, "0600");
}

private byte[] GetMachineSpecificKey()
{
    // Combine machine ID and user ID for encryption key derivation
    var machineId = File.ReadAllText("/etc/machine-id").Trim();
    var userId = Environment.UserName;
    var combined = $"{machineId}:{userId}";

    using var sha256 = SHA256.Create();
    return sha256.ComputeHash(Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes(combined));
}
```

This fallback provides:
- **AES-256 encryption** for data at rest
- **Machine-specific key derivation** preventing cross-system access
- **File permission restrictions** (chmod 0600) ensuring only the owner can read
- **Per-key file storage** for easy management and deletion

## Best Practices

**1. Handle Unavailability Gracefully:**
```csharp
public async Task<bool> IsSecureStorageAvailableAsync()
{
    try
    {
        await SecureStorage.SetAsync("test_key", "test_value");
        SecureStorage.Remove("test_key");
        return true;
    }
    catch
    {
        return false;
    }
}
```

**2. Don't Store Large Data:**
Secure storage is designed for credentials and tokens, not large files. Keep values under 1KB.

**3. Handle Keyring Locks:**
GNOME Keyring and KDE Wallet may be locked, requiring user authentication:

```csharp
try
{
    var token = await SecureStorage.GetAsync("auth_token");
}
catch (Exception ex) when (ex.Message.Contains("locked"))
{
    await DisplayAlert("Keyring Locked", 
        "Please unlock your keyring to access stored credentials.",
        "OK");
}
```

**4. Clear Sensitive Data on Logout:**
```csharp
public async Task LogoutAsync()
{
    SecureStorage.Remove("auth_token");
    SecureStorage.Remove("refresh_token");
    SecureStorage.RemoveAll(); // Clear all app data
}
```

The dual-strategy approach ensures your sensitive data is protected whether users have a full desktop environment with keyring services or a minimal system where encrypted files provide the security layer.

## Clipboard, Launcher, and Share Services

Beyond file pickers and notifications, OpenMaui provides a complete suite of platform services for common desktop integration tasks. These services handle clipboard operations, launching external applications, sharing content, and opening URLs.

## Clipboard Service

Clipboard access on Linux requires different implementations for X11 and Wayland sessions, with command-line fallbacks for maximum compatibility.

**X11 Clipboard Implementation:**
```csharp
public class X11Clipboard : IClipboard
{
    public async Task SetTextAsync(string text)
    {
        // Use X11 selection API
        var display = XOpenDisplay(null);
        var window = XCreateSimpleWindow(display, /* ... */);

        // Set CLIPBOARD selection
        XSetSelectionOwner(display, XA_CLIPBOARD, window, CurrentTime);

        // Store text for selection requests
        _clipboardText = text;

        // Process selection request events
        ProcessSelectionEvents(display, window);
    }

    public async Task<string> GetTextAsync()
    {
        var display = XOpenDisplay(null);
        var window = XCreateSimpleWindow(display, /* ... */);

        // Request CLIPBOARD selection
        XConvertSelection(display, XA_CLIPBOARD, XA_UTF8_STRING, 
            XA_CLIPBOARD, window, CurrentTime);

        // Wait for SelectionNotify event
        return await WaitForSelectionAsync(display, window);
    }
}
```

**Wayland Clipboard:**
Wayland uses the wl-clipboard tools (wl-copy/wl-paste):

```csharp
public async Task SetTextAsync(string text)
{
    var process = new Process
    {
        StartInfo = new ProcessStartInfo
        {
            FileName = "wl-copy",
            RedirectStandardInput = true,
            UseShellExecute = false
        }
    };

    process.Start();
    await process.StandardInput.WriteAsync(text);
    process.StandardInput.Close();
    await process.WaitForExitAsync();
}

public async Task<string> GetTextAsync()
{
    var process = new Process
    {
        StartInfo = new ProcessStartInfo
        {
            FileName = "wl-paste",
            Arguments = "--no-newline",
            RedirectStandardOutput = true,
            UseShellExecute = false
        }
    };

    process.Start();
    var text = await process.StandardOutput.ReadToEndAsync();
    await process.WaitForExitAsync();
    return text;
}
```

**Usage in Your App:**
```csharp
public async Task CopyToClipboardAsync(string text)
{
    await Clipboard.SetTextAsync(text);
    await Toast.Make("Copied to clipboard").Show();
}

public async Task PasteFromClipboardAsync()
{
    if (Clipboard.HasText)
    {
        var text = await Clipboard.GetTextAsync();
        MyEntry.Text = text;
    }
}

// Check clipboard contents
public async Task<bool> HasUrlInClipboard()
{
    var text = await Clipboard.GetTextAsync();
    return Uri.TryCreate(text, UriKind.Absolute, out _);
}
```

## Launcher Service

The Launcher service opens files and URIs with the user's default applications, using the `xdg-open` standard:

```csharp
public class LinuxLauncher : ILauncher
{
    public async Task<bool> OpenAsync(string uri)
    {
        return await OpenViaXdgOpenAsync(uri);
    }

    public async Task<bool> OpenAsync(OpenFileRequest request)
    {
        return await OpenViaXdgOpenAsync(request.File.FullPath);
    }

    private async Task<bool> OpenViaXdgOpenAsync(string target)
    {
        var process = new Process
        {
            StartInfo = new ProcessStartInfo
            {
                FileName = "xdg-open",
                Arguments = $"\"{target}\"",
                UseShellExecute = false,
                CreateNoWindow = true
            }
        };

        process.Start();
        await process.WaitForExitAsync();
        return process.ExitCode == 0;
    }
}
```

**Common Launcher Scenarios:**
```csharp
// Open URL in default browser
await Launcher.OpenAsync("https://github.com/openmaui/openmaui");

// Open email client
await Launcher.OpenAsync("mailto:support@example.com?subject=Bug Report");

// Open file with default application
await Launcher.OpenAsync(new OpenFileRequest
{
    File = new ReadOnlyFile("/home/user/document.pdf")
});

// Open file manager at specific location
await Launcher.OpenAsync($"file:///home/user/Documents");

// Check if URI can be opened
var canOpen = await Launcher.CanOpenAsync("https://example.com");
if (canOpen)
{
    await Launcher.OpenAsync("https://example.com");
}
```

## Share Service

The Share service allows your application to share content with other applications. On Linux, this uses desktop-specific share dialogs:

```csharp
public class LinuxShare : IShare
{
    public async Task RequestAsync(ShareTextRequest request)
    {
        if (IsXdgEmailAvailable())
        {
            // Use xdg-email for text sharing
            await ShareViaEmailAsync(request.Title, request.Text, request.Uri);
        }
        else
        {
            // Copy to clipboard as fallback
            await Clipboard.SetTextAsync(request.Text ?? request.Uri);
            await DisplayShareFallbackAsync();
        }
    }

    public async Task RequestAsync(ShareFileRequest request)
    {
        // Use desktop environment's share portal if available
        if (IsXdgSharePortalAvailable())
        {
            await ShareViaPortalAsync(request.File, request.Title);
        }
        else
        {
            // Open file manager at location
            var directory = Path.GetDirectoryName(request.File.FullPath);
            await Launcher.OpenAsync($"file://{directory}");
        }
    }
}
```

**Sharing Examples:**
```csharp
// Share text
await Share.RequestAsync(new ShareTextRequest
{
    Title = "Check out this link",
    Text = "OpenMaui brings .NET MAUI to Linux!",
    Uri = "https://github.com/openmaui/openmaui"
});

// Share file
await Share.RequestAsync(new ShareFileRequest
{
    Title = "Share Screenshot",
    File = new ShareFile("/home/user/screenshot.png")
});

// Share multiple files
await Share.RequestAsync(new ShareMultipleFilesRequest
{
    Title = "Share Documents",
    Files = new List<ShareFile>
    {
        new ShareFile("/home/user/doc1.pdf"),
        new ShareFile("/home/user/doc2.pdf")
    }
});
```

## Browser Service

For opening URLs specifically in a browser (bypassing other handlers):

```csharp
public async Task OpenInBrowserAsync(string url)
{
    await Browser.OpenAsync(url, new BrowserLaunchOptions
    {
        LaunchMode = BrowserLaunchMode.SystemPreferred,
        TitleMode = BrowserTitleMode.Show,
        PreferredToolbarColor = Colors.Primary,
        PreferredControlColor = Colors.White
    });
}
```

These services work together to provide seamless desktop integration, allowing your MAUI application to interact with the Linux desktop ecosystem using the same APIs you'd use on any other platform.

## Desktop Environment Detection (GNOME/KDE/XFCE)

One of the unique challenges of Linux development is the diversity of desktop environments. Users might be running GNOME, KDE Plasma, XFCE, Cinnamon, MATE, or even minimal window managers like i3 or Openbox. Each environment has different conventions, available services, and theming systems.

OpenMaui provides robust desktop environment detection to adapt behavior and choose the most appropriate integration strategy.

## Environment Detection Strategy

The detection system checks multiple environment variables and process information:

```csharp
public class DesktopEnvironmentDetector
{
    public static DesktopEnvironment Detect()
    {
        // Check standard environment variables
        var xdgCurrentDesktop = Environment.GetEnvironmentVariable("XDG_CURRENT_DESKTOP");
        var desktopSession = Environment.GetEnvironmentVariable("DESKTOP_SESSION");
        var gdmSession = Environment.GetEnvironmentVariable("GDMSESSION");

        // GNOME detection
        if (xdgCurrentDesktop?.Contains("GNOME") == true ||
            desktopSession?.Contains("gnome") == true ||
            IsProcessRunning("gnome-shell"))
        {
            return new DesktopEnvironment
            {
                Type = DesktopType.GNOME,
                Version = DetectGnomeVersion(),
                DisplayServer = DetectDisplayServer(),
                ThemeProvider = "gsettings"
            };
        }

        // KDE Plasma detection
        if (xdgCurrentDesktop?.Contains("KDE") == true ||
            desktopSession?.Contains("plasma") == true ||
            IsProcessRunning("plasmashell"))
        {
            return new DesktopEnvironment
            {
                Type = DesktopType.KDE,
                Version = DetectPlasmaVersion(),
                DisplayServer = DetectDisplayServer(),
                ThemeProvider = "kdeglobals"
            };
        }

        // XFCE detection
        if (xdgCurrentDesktop?.Contains("XFCE") == true ||
            desktopSession?.Contains("xfce") == true ||
            IsProcessRunning("xfce4-panel"))
        {
            return new DesktopEnvironment
            {
                Type = DesktopType.XFCE,
                DisplayServer = DisplayServer.X11,
                ThemeProvider = "xfconf"
            };
        }

        // Fallback to generic
        return new DesktopEnvironment
        {
            Type = DesktopType.Unknown,
            DisplayServer = DetectDisplayServer(),
            ThemeProvider = "none"
        };
    }

    private static DisplayServer DetectDisplayServer()
    {
        var waylandDisplay = Environment.GetEnvironmentVariable("WAYLAND_DISPLAY");
        var sessionType = Environment.GetEnvironmentVariable("XDG_SESSION_TYPE");

        if (!string.IsNullOrEmpty(waylandDisplay) || sessionType == "wayland")
            return DisplayServer.Wayland;

        return DisplayServer.X11;
    }
}
```

## Adapting to Desktop Environments

Once the environment is detected, OpenMaui adapts its behavior:

**File Picker Selection:**
```csharp
public IFilePicker CreateFilePicker()
{
    var desktop = DesktopEnvironmentDetector.Detect();

    return desktop.Type switch
    {
        DesktopType.GNOME => new FilePickerChain(
            new XdgPortalFilePicker(),
            new ZenityFilePicker(),
            new GtkFileChooserPicker()
        ),
        DesktopType.KDE => new FilePickerChain(
            new XdgPortalFilePicker(),
            new KDialogFilePicker(),
            new QtFileDialogPicker()
        ),
        DesktopType.XFCE => new FilePickerChain(
            new ZenityFilePicker(),
            new XdgPortalFilePicker()
        ),
        _ => new FilePickerChain(
            new XdgPortalFilePicker(),
            new ZenityFilePicker(),
            new KDialogFilePicker()
        )
    };
}
```

**Theme Detection:**
```csharp
public class ThemeDetector
{
    public AppTheme DetectTheme()
    {
        var desktop = DesktopEnvironmentDetector.Detect();

        return desktop.Type switch
        {
            DesktopType.GNOME => DetectGnomeTheme(),
            DesktopType.KDE => DetectKdeTheme(),
            DesktopType.XFCE => DetectXfceTheme(),
            _ => AppTheme.Unspecified
        };
    }

    private AppTheme DetectGnomeTheme()
    {
        // Use gsettings to query GNOME theme
        var result = ExecuteCommand("gsettings", 
            "get org.gnome.desktop.interface gtk-theme");

        if (result.Contains("dark", StringComparison.OrdinalIgnoreCase))
            return AppTheme.Dark;

        // Check color scheme preference (GNOME 42+)
        var colorScheme = ExecuteCommand("gsettings",
            "get org.gnome.desktop.interface color-scheme");

        return colorScheme.Contains("prefer-dark") 
            ? AppTheme.Dark 
            : AppTheme.Light;
    }

    private AppTheme DetectKdeTheme()
    {
        // Read KDE config file
        var kdeglobals = Path.Combine(
            Environment.GetFolderPath(Environment.SpecialFolder.UserProfile),
            ".config/kdeglobals"
        );

        if (File.Exists(kdeglobals))
        {
            var content = File.ReadAllText(kdeglobals);
            if (content.Contains("[ColorScheme]"))
            {
                // Parse color scheme
                var colorScheme = ParseKdeColorScheme(content);
                return colorScheme.IsDark ? AppTheme.Dark : AppTheme.Light;
            }
        }

        return AppTheme.Unspecified;
    }
}
```

## Display Server Detection

Knowing whether the application is running on X11 or Wayland is crucial for choosing the right APIs:

```csharp
public class DisplayServerDetector
{
    public static DisplayServer Detect()
    {
        // Check environment variables
        if (!string.IsNullOrEmpty(Environment.GetEnvironmentVariable("WAYLAND_DISPLAY")))
            return DisplayServer.Wayland;

        if (!string.IsNullOrEmpty(Environment.GetEnvironmentVariable("DISPLAY")))
            return DisplayServer.X11;

        // Try to connect to Wayland
        if (TryConnectWayland())
            return DisplayServer.Wayland;

        // Try to connect to X11
        if (TryConnectX11())
            return DisplayServer.X11;

        return DisplayServer.Unknown;
    }
}
```

## Practical Usage in Applications

You can use environment detection to customize your application's behavior:

```csharp
public partial class App : Application
{
    public App()
    {
        InitializeComponent();

        var desktop = DesktopEnvironmentDetector.Detect();

        // Adapt UI based on desktop environment
        if (desktop.Type == DesktopType.GNOME)
        {
            // Use GNOME-style header bars
            Application.Current.Resources["UseHeaderBar"] = true;
        }
        else if (desktop.Type == DesktopType.KDE)
        {
            // Use traditional menu bars for KDE
            Application.Current.Resources["UseMenuBar"] = true;
        }

        // Adapt to display server
        if (desktop.DisplayServer == DisplayServer.Wayland)
        {
            // Disable X11-specific features
            Application.Current.Resources["EnableGlobalHotkeys"] = false;
        }

        // Set theme based on desktop preference
        Application.Current.UserAppTheme = DetectSystemTheme();

        MainPage = new AppShell();
    }
}
```

## HiDPI and Scaling Detection

Different desktop environments handle HiDPI scaling differently:

```csharp
public class DpiDetector
{
    public static double DetectScaleFactor()
    {
        var desktop = DesktopEnvironmentDetector.Detect();

        return desktop.Type switch
        {
            DesktopType.GNOME => DetectGnomeScaling(),
            DesktopType.KDE => DetectKdeScaling(),
            DesktopType.XFCE => DetectXfceScaling(),
            _ => 1.0
        };
    }

    private static double DetectGnomeScaling()
    {
        var scaling = ExecuteCommand("gsettings",
            "get org.gnome.desktop.interface scaling-factor");

        if (uint.TryParse(scaling, out var factor))
            return factor;

        // Fallback to text scaling
        var textScaling = ExecuteCommand("gsettings",
            "get org.gnome.desktop.interface text-scaling-factor");

        return double.TryParse(textScaling, out var textFactor) 
            ? textFactor 
            : 1.0;
    }
}
```

This comprehensive detection system ensures your application feels native regardless of which desktop environment your users prefer, while gracefully handling edge cases and minimal installations.

## Handling Service Availability and Graceful Degradation

The most critical aspect of Linux platform services isn't just implementing the features—it's handling the reality that services may be unavailable, partially functional, or configured differently across distributions and desktop environments.

OpenMaui's architecture is built around **graceful degradation**: every service has multiple implementation strategies, and the platform automatically selects the best available option.

## Service Availability Detection

Before attempting to use a service, OpenMaui checks whether it's available:

```csharp
public class ServiceAvailability
{
    private readonly Dictionary<string, bool> _availabilityCache = new();

    public bool IsServiceAvailable(string serviceName)
    {
        if (_availabilityCache.TryGetValue(serviceName, out var cached))
            return cached;

        var available = CheckServiceAvailability(serviceName);
        _availabilityCache[serviceName] = available;
        return available;
    }

    private bool CheckServiceAvailability(string serviceName)
    {
        return serviceName switch
        {
            "xdg-desktop-portal" => IsDbusServiceAvailable(
                "org.freedesktop.portal.Desktop"),
            "libsecret" => IsDbusServiceAvailable(
                "org.freedesktop.secrets"),
            "notifications" => IsDbusServiceAvailable(
                "org.freedesktop.Notifications"),
            "zenity" => IsCommandAvailable("zenity"),
            "kdialog" => IsCommandAvailable("kdialog"),
            "notify-send" => IsCommandAvailable("notify-send"),
            _ => false
        };
    }

    private bool IsDbusServiceAvailable(string serviceName)
    {
        try
        {
            var result = ExecuteCommand("dbus-send",
                $"--session --dest={serviceName} --type=method_call " +
                $"--print-reply / org.freedesktop.DBus.Peer.Ping");
            return result.ExitCode == 0;
        }
        catch
        {
            return false;
        }
    }

    private bool IsCommandAvailable(string command)
    {
        try
        {
            var result = ExecuteCommand("which", command);
            return result.ExitCode == 0;
        }
        catch
        {
            return false;
        }
    }
}
```

## Fallback Chain Pattern

Each platform service implements a fallback chain that tries multiple strategies in order of preference:

```csharp
public abstract class PlatformServiceBase<T>
{
    protected async Task<TResult> ExecuteWithFallbackAsync<TResult>(
        params Func<Task<TResult>>[] strategies)
    {
        Exception lastException = null;

        foreach (var strategy in strategies)
        {
            try
            {
                var result = await strategy();
                if (result != null)
                    return result;
            }
            catch (Exception ex)
            {
                lastException = ex;
                // Log but continue to next strategy
                LogFallback(strategy.Method.Name, ex);
            }
        }

        // All strategies failed
        throw new PlatformNotSupportedException(
            "All service implementations failed. " +
            "Please install xdg-desktop-portal or desktop-specific tools.",
            lastException
        );
    }
}
```

## Example: Comprehensive File Picker Fallback

Here's how the file picker implements the complete fallback chain:

```csharp
public class LinuxFilePicker : PlatformServiceBase<IFilePicker>, IFilePicker
{
    public async Task<FileResult> PickAsync(PickOptions options = null)
    {
        return await ExecuteWithFallbackAsync(
            // Strategy 1: Modern portal (works in sandboxed apps)
            async () => await PickViaXdgPortalAsync(options),

            // Strategy 2: GNOME/GTK environments
            async () => await PickViaZenityAsync(options),

            // Strategy 3: KDE Plasma
            async () => await PickViaKDialogAsync(options),

            // Strategy 4: GTK native dialog (requires GTK3)
            async () => await PickViaGtkDialogAsync(options),

            // Strategy 5: Last resort - manual path entry
            async () => await PickViaManualEntryAsync(options)
        );
    }

    private async Task<FileResult> PickViaManualEntryAsync(PickOptions options)
    {
        // Show a simple dialog asking user to enter file path
        var path = await DisplayPromptAsync(
            "Select File",
            "Enter the full path to the file:",
            initialValue: Environment.GetFolderPath(
                Environment.SpecialFolder.UserProfile)
        );

        if (string.IsNullOrEmpty(path) || !File.Exists(path))
            return null;

        return new FileResult(path);
    }
}
```

